<dl id="un7011ct"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un7" href="#un7011">UN7: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un7all.htm#un7011ct"> (V.A.2) 11(ct)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Saloon motor hearse, <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un7011ct"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/q/lexq.htm#un7011ct">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/q/q86.htm#un7011ct">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/q/q86.htm#un7011ct">1986 (15.1687)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/q/l22q.htm#un7011ct">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#un7011ct">MS PL-1</ms> </li><li>JJA 20:064 </li><li><a name="qd8" href="../udra/u15da.htm#qd8">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/q/qd8.htm#un7011ct">Draft: 15.8</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Hearses remained horse-drawn until the first decade of the twentieth century, when motorized hearses began to appear. The first were electric. Those using an internal combustion engine did not appear until 1909, at the funeral of Wilfrid A. Pruyn. The undertaker responsible was H.D. Ludlow, who commissioned a vehicle to be built out of the body of a horse-drawn hearse and the chassis of a bus. This new type of hearse was quite popular with the funeral home&apos;s wealthier customers and Ludlow used it for thirteen more funerals before replacing it with a larger model. See also <a name="un6006ab" href="un6all.htm#un6006ab">UN6 (NLI.4):006(ab)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
